====== Compilers & Runners ======

Meow supports two extension points:
  * **Compilers** (`ICompiler`) — convert source files into object files and optionally link into final artifacts.
  * **Runners** (`IRunner`) — execute interpreted/script languages directly.

===== Built-in compilers =====
  * `masm` — MASM assembler
  * `c`, `cpp` — C/C++ compilers
  * `fortran`, `objectfortran` — Fortran compilers
  * `java` — Java (`javac`)
  * `go` — Go (`go build`)
  * `rust` — Rust (`cargo` / `rustc`)
  * `csharp` — C# (`dotnet build` / `csc`)
  * `fusion`, `sharpir`, `uhigh`, `objectivepascal` — domain-specific compilers

===== Built-in runners =====
  * `python` — runs `.py` using `python` or `python3`
  * `node` — runs `.js` using `node` or `deno`

===== How Meow chooses an implementation =====
  * `build.compiler` in `meow.yaml` names either a compiler or a runner.
  * `BuildService.CreateCompiler` and `CreateRunner` instantiate implementations by name.

===== Adding a new compiler/runner =====
  1. Implement `ICompiler` (compiler) or `IRunner` (runner) in `src/Meow.Core/Compilers`.
  2. Register the implementation in `BuildService.CreateCompiler` or `CreateRunner`.
  3. Add unit tests and documentation in `docs/` describing any required external toolchains.
  4. Optionally implement `ITemplateProvider` to provide `meow init` templates.

===== Dependency categories =====
Compilers may declare supported dependency categories (e.g., `runtime`, `nuget`, `java`). Use `dependencyCategories` in `meow.yaml` to categorize packages; Meow will warn if a category is unsupported by the chosen compiler.

